  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Early Childhood Education Program</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Displaced children ages 3-5</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Fond Parisien is located in an OCHA designated area of high-priority for education. After the earthquake, it experienced an influx of more than 5,000 people - stretching local schools beyond capacity. A community census revealed that 350 children (ages 3-5) lacked access to education. JRS partnered with local Vedruna Sisters who already managed a successful preschool with 60 students and teachers. Operating the school out of a local chapel, the Sisters could only enroll more students if they had  a larger school building. Through JRS support, the Sisters have built a new school and education has been expanded to the children of the displaced, vulnerable single mothers, and local poor families identified by the census. In addition to lessons, the school provides students with two meals a day. Now 135 new students have access to education and nutrition.</narrative>
  </description>
